What is "Scope" in JavaScript? (12:00)

Answer: Scope determines the accessibility of variables.
Types: Global Scope (accessible everywhere), Function Scope (accessible only inside a function), and Block Scope (introduced by let/const inside curly braces {}).
II. Advanced JavaScript Concepts (0:12:36 - 0:46:23)
What is a Closure? (12:36)

Answer: A closure gives a function access to its outer scope even after the outer function has finished executing. It is essentially a function "remembering" its lexical environment.
What is the difference between == and ===? (14:30)

== (Abstract Equality): Compares values after performing type coercion (e.g., 5 == "5" is true).
=== (Strict Equality): Compares both value and data type without coercion (e.g., 5 === "5" is false).
Explain GraphQL vs. REST API. (16:01)

REST: Uses multiple endpoints for different data. Often leads to over-fetching (getting more data than needed) (16:45).
GraphQL: Uses a single endpoint. The client requests exactly what they need, making it more efficient for complex data (17:30).
What are the components of the CSS Box Model? (18:51)

Answer: Every HTML element is treated as a box consisting of: Content, Padding (internal space), Border, and Margin (external space) (19:20).
What are the Data Types in JavaScript? (24:04)

Primitive: Number, BigInt, String, Boolean, Undefined, Null, and Symbol (24:25).
Non-Primitive: Objects, Arrays, and Functions (27:30).
What is the DOM (Document Object Model)? (28:31)

